<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,836,1835]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,276,836,863]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Males of this species can be differentiated from most others of the genus by the combination of two submarginal cells, metatibial spurs straight, S2 and S3 with straight posterior margins (
<figureCitation box="[1126,1207,873,899]" captionStart="FIGURES 34–40" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1884,1909]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,166,1864]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[168,1419,166,1864]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 34–40. Liphanthus discolor sp. nov., holotype, 34: lateral habitus, 35: face frontal view, 36: upper paraocular area to show absence of facial fovea (arrow to area where this occurs in related species, compare to Figs. 22 &amp; 43), 37: metasomal venter to show brownish colouration and reduced yellow on reflexed portions of terga, 38: S7, 39: S8, 40: genital capsule. Scale bars Figs. 34–35 &amp; 37 1mm, Fig. 36 0.25mm, Figs. 38–40 0.125mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3345463/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
) and ventral surface of the mandibles bearing a tuft of branched hairs at midlength (as in 
<figureCitation box="[926,994,909,935]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1816,1841]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,519,1796]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1435,519,1796]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Unusual morphological features of some Liphanthus species. 1: L. jenamro sp. nov. ESEM of frontal area of holotype male to show minutely and densely tuberculate microsculpture, 2: L. jenamro ESEM of frontal area of allotype female to show acinose (bracket) to minutely and densely tuberculate microsculpture, 3: L. jenamro mandibles of a paratype male to show tuft of specialized hairs at the junction of the outer ridge and ventral margin, note the long branches on one side of the rachis only. Scale bars Figs. 1–2 100μm, Fig. 3 0.25mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3345449/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). It differs from other species with two submarginal cells and a tufted mandible in lacking a facial fovea (
<figureCitation box="[891,973,945,972]" captionStart="FIGURES 34–40" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1884,1909]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,166,1864]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[168,1419,166,1864]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 34–40. Liphanthus discolor sp. nov., holotype, 34: lateral habitus, 35: face frontal view, 36: upper paraocular area to show absence of facial fovea (arrow to area where this occurs in related species, compare to Figs. 22 &amp; 43), 37: metasomal venter to show brownish colouration and reduced yellow on reflexed portions of terga, 38: S7, 39: S8, 40: genital capsule. Scale bars Figs. 34–35 &amp; 37 1mm, Fig. 36 0.25mm, Figs. 38–40 0.125mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3345463/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 36</figureCitation>
) and lacking yellow markings to the side of T2 (
<figureCitation box="[227,312,981,1007]" captionStart="FIGURES 34–40" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1884,1909]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,166,1864]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[168,1419,166,1864]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 34–40. Liphanthus discolor sp. nov., holotype, 34: lateral habitus, 35: face frontal view, 36: upper paraocular area to show absence of facial fovea (arrow to area where this occurs in related species, compare to Figs. 22 &amp; 43), 37: metasomal venter to show brownish colouration and reduced yellow on reflexed portions of terga, 38: S7, 39: S8, 40: genital capsule. Scale bars Figs. 34–35 &amp; 37 1mm, Fig. 36 0.25mm, Figs. 38–40 0.125mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3345463/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
