</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,152,1727]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1161,1187]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific epithet refers to the fact that the sole specimen known has the pale markings mostly orange, presumably as a result of prolonged exposure to cyanide. This should be born in mind when considering the colour in the images.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,152,1727]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1268,1295]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Comments.</emphasis>
Using the key in 
<bibRefCitation author="Ruz, L. &amp; Toro, H." box="[527,759,1269,1295]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="235 - 299" refId="ref44762" refString="Ruz, L. &amp; Toro, H. (1983) Revision of the bee genus Liphanthus (Hymenoptera: Andrenidae). University of Kansas Science Bulletin, 52, 235 - 299." type="journal article" year="1983">Ruz and Toro (1983)</bibRefCitation>
, if treated as having three submarginal cells, this species fails at couplet 
<quantity box="[268,311,1305,1331]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.032" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" unit="in" value="8.0">8 in</quantity>
that it has the short F1 of the second lead but the flat clypeal profile of the first.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,152,1727]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
The area just south of Vicuña is quite famous due to the extensive collecting that has been performed in the area, resulting in studies of a number of rare bees, including 
<taxonomicName authority="Friese 1925" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1925" box="[755,1122,1376,1403]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Euherbstia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="excellens">
<emphasis box="[755,987,1377,1403]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Euherbstia excellens</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Friese, H." box="[992,1122,1376,1403]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 41" refId="ref43580" refString="Friese, H. (1925) Neue neotropische Bienenarten, zugleich II. Nachtung zur Bienenfauna von Costa Rica. Stettiner Entomologische Zietung, 86, 1 - 41." type="journal article" year="1925">Friese 1925</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Rozen, J. G. Jr." box="[1135,1273,1377,1403]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 17" refId="ref44594" refString="Rozen, J. G. Jr. (1993) Phylogenetic relationships of Euherbstia with other short-tongued bees. American Museum Novitates, 3060, 1 - 17." type="journal article" year="1993">Rozen 1993</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName authority="Ruz 1995 in Rozen &amp; Ruz (1995)" authorityName="Ruz 1995 in Rozen &amp; Ruz" authorityYear="1995" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Neffapis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longilingua">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Neffapis longilingua</emphasis>
Ruz 
<quantity box="[303,387,1412,1439]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0673" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" unit="in" value="1995.0">1995 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Rozen, J. G. Jr. &amp; Ruz, L." box="[393,628,1412,1439]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 15" refId="ref44702" refString="Rozen, J. G. Jr. &amp; Ruz, L. (1995) South American panurgine bees (Andrenidae: Panurginae), Part II. Adults, immature stages, and biology of Neffapis longilingua, a new genus and species with an elongate glossa. American Museum Novitates, 3136, 1 - 15." type="journal article" year="1995">Rozen &amp; Ruz (1995)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Toro (1976)" authorityName="Toro" authorityYear="1976" box="[686,1077,1413,1440]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Chilimalopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parvula">
<emphasis box="[686,935,1413,1439]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Chilimalopsis parvula</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Toro, H." box="[941,1077,1413,1440]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="73 - 76" refId="ref44924" refString="Toro, H. (1976) Chilimalopsis, nuevo genero chileno de Exomalopsini. Anales del Museo de Historia Natural de Valparaiso, 9, 73 - 76." type="journal article" year="1976">Toro (1976)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Thus, the fact that only a single male is known suggests that this may be a rare or highly habitat restricted species. Considerable additional collecting has been performed in the area since 2001, but the species has not been rediscovered. Since 2001 the north end of the original locality has been more extensively developed for grape growing and there is also a large garbage dump closer to the 
<typeStatus box="[366,414,1557,1583]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">type</typeStatus>
locality (Packer, personal observations), neither of these developments likely conducive to the sustainability of bee populations.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,152,1727]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Along with the three species described above and a number of undescribed species with three submarginal cells, this species forms a species group characterized, in males, by the presence of a hair tuft on the ventral margin of the mandible at the end of a strongly lamellate outer ridge and a minutely tuberculate frontal area.</paragraph>
